01:37:43,140 --> 01:37:45,220
if s is equal to minus one.

2546
01:37:49,120 --> 01:37:50,200
See what that means.

2547
01:37:50,940 --> 01:37:52,800
Let's take the case plus one.

2548
01:37:57,679 --> 01:38:00,020
I think I'm beginning to fade.

2549
01:38:00,140 --> 01:38:01,220
I think it's time to quit.

2550
01:38:01,340 --> 01:38:03,640
I think you're probably also beginning to fade.

2551
01:38:03,860 --> 01:38:06,860
We'll go through fermions and bosons next time.

2552
01:38:07,080 --> 01:38:09,240
But the basic idea is

2553
01:38:09,240 --> 01:38:11,400
classifying the wave functions of particles

2554
01:38:11,400 --> 01:38:15,480
in terms of what happens when you switch the particles.

2555
01:38:16,440 --> 01:38:18,860
It's a basic quantum mechanical process

2556
01:38:18,860 --> 01:38:20,920
or a basic quantum mechanical operation

2557
01:38:20,920 --> 01:38:23,100
the swapping of particles.

2558
01:38:23,980 --> 01:38:24,620
And

2559
01:38:26,800 --> 01:38:29,060
the notion of identical particles

2560
01:38:29,800 --> 01:38:32,760
is basically telling you that something simple happens

2561
01:38:32,760 --> 01:38:34,340
when you swap two particles.

2562
01:38:35,900 --> 01:38:37,720
Either the wave function does this

2563
01:38:37,720 --> 01:38:38,740
or it does that.

2564
01:38:38,860 --> 01:38:40,040
And we'll do it next week.

